so, examining the existing [calculateDependentResources](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/1387afec8fbed2b74f7cf3b0d06bf24f2ce22f66/pkg/resource/deploy/step_generator.go#L889) logic, it appeared to not actually provide value as far as i could see.  It was already doing something similar to what i do here (looking at the dep-graph to determine downstream affected resources).  But i couldn't identify a scenario where it was valuable to only work with these resources.

For example, in the tests here: https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/master/pkg/engine/lifecycle_test.go#L2625

```
	//             A
	//    _________|_________
	//    B        C        D
	//          ___|___  ___|___
	//          E  F  G  H  I  J
	//             |__|
	//             K  L
	//
	// For a given resource R in (A, C, D):
	// - R will be the provider for its first dependent
	// - A change to R will require that its second dependent be replaced
	// - A change to R will not require that its third dependent be replaced
	//
	// In addition, K will have a requires-replacement property that depends on both F and G, and
	// L will have a normal property that depends on both F and G.
```

the code that handles delete-before-replace identifies `B, C, E, F, and K` as needing replacement for when 'A' is affected.  However, if 'A' is deleted, we still need to deal with 'D' still having a dep on 'A'.  If we do not handle it, then we'll have a dangling ref.

It simply seemed sensible to me (but it sounds like i missed something) that asking to destroy a resource A would necessarily destroy what was necessary in order to be able to properly get rid of that resource itself.  

